The West African Post Graduate College of Medical Laboratory Science has expressed its preparedness to collaborate with the Economic Community of West African States, (ECOWAS) in a bid to tackle quackery in the profession. The registrar, West African Post Graduate College of Medical Laboratory Science, Dr. Goodwill Ovara, who disclosed this at the College Regional Council Meeting, in Lagos, said for the African region to standardize the practice of the profession, the collaboration cannot be over-emphasized. Ovara said fake laboratory scientists are everywhere in Nigeria, adding that the Association of Medical Laboratory Scientists of Nigeria (AMLSN), has tried severally to carry out an inspection on all laboratory facilities in Nigeria, but there have been some form of resistance. “We have noticed that if 10 people go to a laboratory to test for malaria, nine persons out of the 10, would be diagnosed with malaria and typhoid. Malaria and Typhoid are over diagnosed; over-treated in Nigeria. “To tackle that issue, there was a time when the AMLSN taskforce went on an inspection of laboratory facilities in Nigeria, which is in line with the law, but many private clinics resisted them. They started calling the federal ministry of health, and before we knew, the special team were asked to step down. “So with that kind of situation, when authorities who are supposed to hold this people accountable of their actions, are the ones protecting them, the innocent public will be at the receiving end,” he added. The registrar said the West African laboratory scientists, have agreed that going forward, the ECOWAS Authorities and the West African Health Organization will now look up to the West African College of Medical Laboratory Science for advice, guidance and for policy initiation. 